'''Michael Monroe Lewis''' (born October 15, 1960) is an American [[financial journalist]] and bestselling [[non-fiction]] author.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://authors.simonandschuster.com/Michael-Lewis/4349 |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |title=Michael Lewis author page |accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref>  He has also been a contributing editor to ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' since 2009.

==Early life==
Lewis was born in [[New Orleans]], the son of [[corporate lawyer]] J. Thomas Lewis and [[community activist]] Diana Monroe Lewis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-life-of-michael-lewis-2012-6|title=The Amazing Life Of Wall Street's Favorite Writer, Michael Lewis|author=|date=|website=businessinsider.com|accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref> He attended [[Princeton University]] where he earned a [[cum laude]] bachelor's degree in [[art history]] in 1982 and was a member of the [[Ivy Club]].<ref name=Diane_wedding/> He went on to work with New York City art dealer [[Daniel Wildenstein]] for a short while. In an interview with Charlie Rose, Lewis shared that his initial ambition was to become an art historian, but was quickly dissuaded once he realized that there were no jobs available for art historians and even the handful would not pay much.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rose|first1=Charlie|title=Interview with Michael Lewis|url=https://charlierose.com/videos/31161|website=www.charlierose.com|publisher=Charlie Rose|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>

Lewis subsequently enrolled at the [[London School of Economics]] and received an [[Master of Arts|MA]] in [[economics]] in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatertalent.com/MichaelLewis/|title=Michael Lewis |publisher=[[Greater Talent Network (GTN)|Greater Talent Network]] Speakers Bureau |accessdate=2012-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=[[Contemporary Authors Online]] |publisher=[[Gale (publisher)|Gale]] |year=2011 |location=Detroit |chapter=Michael Lewis |accessdate=2012-03-04 |chapter-url=http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/ReferenceDetailsPage/ReferenceDetailsWindow?displayGroupName=Reference&disableHighlighting=false&prodId=BIC1&action=e&windowstate=normal&catId=&documentId=GALE%7CH1000059769&mode=view&userGroupName=fairfax_main&jsid=79fc6c90ca7fafc7735a82db82279d9a |id=GALE&#124;H1000059769 | via= Fairfax County Public Library}} Gale Biography In Context. {{subscription}}</ref> Lewis was hired by [[Salomon Brothers]], stayed for a while in New York for their training program and then relocated to [[London]] where he worked at Salomon's London office as a bond salesman for a few years.<ref name="imf">{{cite web|title=One on one with Christine Lagarde, featuring Michael Lewis|url=https://www.imf.org/external/POS_Meetings/SeminarDetails.aspx?SeminarId=186|website=www.imf.org|publisher=IMF (International monetary fund)|accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref>

==Writing==
Lewis described his experiences at Salomon and the evolution of the [[Mortgage-backed security|mortgage-backed bond]] in ''[[Liar's Poker]]'' (1989). In ''[[The New New Thing]]'' (1999), he investigated the then-booming [[Silicon Valley]] and discussed obsession with innovation. Four years later, Lewis wrote ''[[Moneyball]]'', in which he investigated the success of [[Billy Beane]] and the [[Oakland Athletics|Oakland A's]]. In August 2007, he wrote an article about [[catastrophe bond]]s entitled "In Nature's Casino" that appeared in ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/26/magazine/26neworleans-t.html | work=[[New York City|The New York Times Magazine]] | title=In Nature's Casino | first=Michael | last=Lewis | date=2007-08-26 | accessdate=2010-05-12}}</ref>

Lewis has worked for ''[[The Spectator]]'',<ref name=Writer_Directory/> ''The New York Times Magazine'', as a columnist for [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]], as a senior editor and campaign correspondent to ''[[The New Republic]]'',<ref name="Future Just Happened">{{cite news|title=the future just happened|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/in_depth/programmes/2001/future/lewis.stm|work=BBC|publisher=BBC|accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref> and a visiting fellow at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. He wrote the ''Dad Again'' column for ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''. Lewis worked for [[Conde Nast Portfolio]] but in February 2009 left to join ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', where he became a contributing editor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.observer.com/2008/media/graydon-s-big-get-raids-portfolio-michael-lewis |title=Graydon's Big Get: Raids Portfolio for Michael Lewis |author=John Koblin |date=October 7, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415010556/http://www.observer.com/2008/media/graydon-s-big-get-raids-portfolio-michael-lewis |archivedate=April 15, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/bios/michael_lewis/search?contributorName=Michael%20Lewis |title=Michael Lewis |work=''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' |accessdate=July 20, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090711100318/http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/bios/michael_lewis/search?contributorName=Michael%20Lewis |archivedate=July 11, 2009 }}</ref>

In September 2011, after the successful release of the [[Moneyball (film)|film adaptation]] of his book ''Moneyball'', it was reported that Lewis planned to take on "a much more active role in the what could be the next film based on one of his books" and would start writing a script for a ''Liar's Poker'' film.<ref name="Liars Poker Script">{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Andy|title='Moneyball' Author Michael Lewis to Script 'Liar's Poker' for Warner Bros. (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/moneyball-author-michael-lewis-script-240026|accessdate=14 November 2012|newspaper=Hollywood Reporter|date=26 September 2011|author2=Matt Belloni}}</ref><ref name="Turned Into a Film">{{cite news|last=Ross|first=Scott|title=Michael Lewis' "Liar's Poker" Being Turned Into a Film by Requa & Ficarra|url=http://www.nbcbayarea.com/blogs/popcornbiz/Michael-Lewis-Liars-Poker-Following-Moneyball-and-The-Blind-Side-to-Big-Screen-130590553.html|accessdate=17 January 2013|newspaper=NBC Bay Area|date=30 May 2012}}</ref>

In 2013, in ''Vanity Fair'', Lewis wrote on the injustice of the prosecution of ex-[[Goldman Sachs]] programmer [[Sergey Aleynikov]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2013/09/michael-lewis-goldman-sachs-programmer |title= Michael Lewis: Did Goldman Sachs Overstep in Criminally Charging Its Ex-Programmer? |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 2013 |website=VanityFair.com |publisher= |access-date=31 August 2017}}</ref> who is given an entire chapter in ''Flash Boys''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/03/18/ex-goldman-programmer-sentenced-to-8-years-for-theft-of-trading-code |title=Former Goldman Programmer Gets 8-year Jail Term for Code Theft |author=Azam Ahmed |date=March 18, 2011 |website=[[NYTimes.com]] |access-date=5 November 2017 |quote=A former Goldman Sachs computer programmer convicted of stealing source code from the firm was sentenced on Friday to more than eight years in prison, capping a case that had shone a rare spotlight on the world of lightning-fast computer-driven trading.}}</ref> ''Flash Boys'', which looked at [[high-frequency trading]] of Wall Street and other markets, was released in March 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://books.wwnorton.com/books/detail.aspx?ID=4294981104|title=Flash Boys {{!}} W. W. Norton & Company|website=books.wwnorton.com|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref>

In 2018, Lewis wrote and narrated, ''The Coming Storm'' for [[Audible Studios]], who released the short non-fiction story as part of their new Audible Originals series of [[audio books]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.audible.com/pd/The-Coming-Storm-Audiobook/B07F43574T|title=The Coming Storm|last=Lewis|first=Michael|publisher=|year=2018|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>

==Reception==
A best-selling author, Lewis has drawn both supporters and vocal detractors. In a review of ''Moneyball'', [[Dan Ackman]] of ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'' said that Lewis had a special talent: "He can walk into an area already mined by hundreds of writers and find gems there all along but somehow missed by his predecessors".<ref name="Ackman Forbes">{{cite web|last=Ackman|first=Dan|title=''Moneyball: The Art Of Winning An Unfair Game''|url=https://www.forbes.com/2003/05/28/cx_da_0528bookreview.html|work=Forbes|accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref> A ''[[New York Times]]'' piece said that "no one writes with more narrative panache about money and finance than Mr. Lewis", praising his ability to use his subject's stories to show the problems with the systems around them.<ref name="Foresaw the Meltdown">{{cite news|last=Kakutani|first=Michiko|title=Investors Who Foresaw the Meltdown|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/15/books/15book.html|accessdate=14 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=14 March 2010}}</ref>

Lewis has been criticized for writing a 2007 article in ''[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]'' criticizing economists at the [[World Economic Forum]] for expressing views on how the world wasn't pricing risk appropriately.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lewis|first1=Michael|title=Davos Is for Wimps, Ninnies, Pointless Skeptics: Michael Lewis|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aaagOLYMd4yg|publisher=Bloomberg News|date=30 January 2007}}</ref>

Critics from outside the [[financial industry]] have also criticized Lewis for what they consider to be inaccuracies in his writing. In a 2011 column in ''[[The Atlantic]]'', American journalist and sports author [[Allen Barra]] takes issue with Lewis's characterization of [[Major League Baseball]] in his 2003 book ''Moneyball''. Barra writes: "From a historical standpoint, Lewis is, well, way off base. By the end of the 20th century baseball had achieved a greater level of competitive balance than at any time in the game's history... ''Moneyball'' doesn't just get the state of present-day baseball wrong; it also misrepresents the history of the sport."<ref name="Moneyball">{{cite news|last=Barra|first=Allen|title=The Many Problems with 'Moneyball'|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/09/the-many-problems-with-moneyball/245769/|accessdate=13 July 2014|newspaper=New York Times|date=13 July 2014}}</ref>

Lewis's ''[[Flash Boys: A Wall Street Revolt]]'' ignited a new round of controversy surrounding [[high-frequency trading]]. At a [[House Financial Services Committee]] hearing in April 2014, [[Mary Jo White]], former Wall Street insider (as a Debevoise & Plimpton litigations lawyer primarily for Wall Street financial firms),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/24/business/dealbook/sec-hamstrung-by-its-leaders-legal-ties.html|title=She Runs S.E.C. He's a Lawyer. Recusals and Headaches Ensue.|author=|date=23 February 2015|publisher=|accessdate=29 April 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> who later served as the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) Chair, denied the theme of Lewis's book, stating that "The markets are not rigged."<ref name="MJWhite">{{cite news|last=Lynch|first=Sarah H.|title=SEC chair to Congress: 'The markets are not rigged'|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/04/29/us-sec-highspeed-trading-idUSBREA3S0OO20140429|accessdate=10 June 2014|newspaper=Reuters|date=29 April 2014}}</ref> One month later, in June 2014, White announced that the [[US Security and Exchange Commission|SEC]] would undergo a new round of regulatory review in response to concerns about [[dark pools]] and market structure.<ref name="SECreview">{{cite news|last=Alden|first=William|title=S.E.C. Chief Offers Rules to Govern Fast Trading |url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/05/s-e-c-chief-calls-for-sweeping-changes-to-stock-market-rules/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|accessdate=10 June 2014|newspaper=New York Times|date=5 June 2014}}</ref>

Lewis's ''[[The Undoing Project]]'' was widely praised by book critics,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lithub.com/bookmarks/reviews/the-undoing-project-a-friendship-that-changed-our-minds/|title=Bookmarks reviews of The Undoing Project by Michael Lewis|publisher=LitHub|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> with [[Glenn C. Altschuler]] arguing in the ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' that it "may well be his best book."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/ae/books/2017/01/15/The-Undoing-Project-How-two-Israeli-psychologists-changed-the-world/stories/201701150039|title='The Undoing Project': How two Israeli psychologists changed the world|last=Altschuler|first=Glenn C.|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=January 15, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Lewis has been married three times. He was married to Diane de Cordova Lewis<ref name=Diane_wedding>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=Diane deCordova Wed at Princeton |date=December 29, 1985 |accessdate=2012-03-04 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/12/29/style/diane-decordova-wed-at-princeton.html}}</ref> and then to former [[CNBC]] correspondent [[Kate Bohner]].<ref>{{cite book|title=[[The Last Tycoons: The Secret History of Lazard Freres & Co.]]|last=Cohan|first=William D.|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|page=401|pages=|chapter=14: It's a White Man's World|authorlink=William D. Cohan}}</ref> He married former [[MTV]] reporter [[Tabitha Soren]] on October 4, 1997. He and Soren have two daughters and one son. They reside in [[Berkeley, California]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vanityfair.com/business/features/2010/10/greeks-bearing-bonds-201010| title = Beware of Greeks Bearing Bonds  | work = ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' |first=Michael |last=Lewis |date=October 1, 2010 | accessdate = December 14, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/aug/08/news/cl-31629/3|accessdate=2012-03-05|title=What's Next for Michael Lewis?|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 8, 2001|authorlink=Shawn Hubler |first=Shawn |last=Hubler}}</ref> Lewis is an [[atheist]].<ref>[[Lewis, Michael]]. ''[[Boomerang: Travels in the New Third World]]''. W.W. Norton and Company, 2011, hardback, {{ISBN|978-0-393-08181-7}}, page 58.</ref><ref>Lewis, Michael (October 1, 2010). [http://www.vanityfair.com/business/features/2010/10/greeks-bearing-bonds-201010 "Beware of Greeks Bearing Bonds"]. ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''. P. 4 of 8.</ref>

